05014nam a22008775i 9780231544504DE-B159720190516114113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||190516s2017    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802315445047 a10.7312/khvo183022doi  a(DE-B1597)480270  a(OCoLC)967457569  a(OCoLC)984688290  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPG3447.V47 7aLCO0140002bisacsh 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a891.73/31 aKhvoshchinskaya, Sofia, eauthor.10aCity Folk and Country Folk /cSofia Khvoshchinskaya. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRussian Library00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction / rHoogenboom, Hilde -- tNotes on the Translation -- tPart I. City Folk and Country Folk -- t1 -- t2 -- t3 -- t4 -- t5 -- t6 -- t7 -- t8 -- t9 -- t10 -- tPART II. City Folk and Country Folk -- t11 -- t12 -- t13 -- t14 -- t15 -- t16 -- t17 -- t18 -- t19  aAn unsung gem of nineteenth-century Russian literature, City Folk and Country Folk is a seemingly gentle yet devastating satire of Russia's aristocratic and pseudo-intellectual elites in the 1860s. Translated into English for the first time, the novel weaves an engaging tale of manipulation, infatuation, and female assertiveness that takes place one year after the liberation of the empire's serfs.Upending Russian literary clichés of female passivity and rural gentry benightedness, Sofia Khvoshchinskaya centers her story on a common-sense, hardworking noblewoman and her self-assured daughter living on their small rural estate. The antithesis of the thoughtful, intellectual, and self-denying young heroines created by Khvoshchinskaya's male peers, especially Ivan Turgenev, seventeen-year-old Olenka ultimately helps her mother overcome a sense of duty to her "betters" and leads the two to triumph over the urbanites' financial, amorous, and matrimonial machinations.Sofia Khvoshchinskaya and her writer sisters closely mirror Britain's Brontës, yet Khvoshchinskaya's work contains more of Jane Austen's wit and social repartee, as well as an intellectual engagement reminiscent of Elizabeth Gaskell's condition-of-England novels. Written by a woman under a male pseudonym, this brilliant and entertaining exploration of gender dynamics on a post-emancipation Russian estate offers a fresh and necessary point of comparison with the better-known classics of nineteenth-century world literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 16. Mai 2019) 0aCountry lifezRussiaxHistoryy19th centuryvFiction. 0aGentryzRussiavFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFavorov, Nora.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2016-2018z978311066255908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook Package 2017z978311065472108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311054330808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Studies 2017z9783110548198oZDB-23-DKU40uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/khvo18302423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780231544504.jpg  a978-3-11-054330-8  CUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-065472-1  CUP eBook Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-066255-9  CUP eBook Package 2016-2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE